🤖 *This is an automated response from Repo Assist.*

The issue is a consequence of how `XmlProvider` works as an **erased type provider**: the generated types don't exist at runtime — they all erase to `FSharp.Data.Runtime.BaseTypes.XmlElement`, which holds an `XDocument` / `XElement` internally. Bolero's remoting serializer sees the runtime type (`XmlElement`), not the logical type you defined, and `System.Xml.Linq.XElement` has no JSON serialization support.

This is a fundamental constraint of erased TPs; it's not something FSharp.Data can easily paper over.

**Recommended workarounds**

**Option 1 — Map to a plain F# record first**

Define a regular record that mirrors the fields you need, and convert before passing over the wire:

```fsharp
type MyXml = XmlProvider<"sample.xml">

// Plain record for serialization
type MyDto = { Name: string; Value: int }

let toDto (node: MyXml.Root) : MyDto =
    { Name = node.Name; Value = node.Value }

// In your Bolero remote service, accept MyDto not MyXml.Root
```

**Option 2 — Pass XML as a string**

Serialize the document to a string on one side and parse it back on the other:

```fsharp
// Sender side
let xmlString = myXmlRoot.XElement.ToString()

// Receiver side (Bolero server)
let parsed = MyXml.Parse(xmlString)
```

The `XElement` property is available on every generated node and gives you the underlying `System.Xml.Linq.XElement`, from which you can call `.ToString()` for round-trip serialization.

**Option 3 — Use a generative type provider (if one exists for your schema)**

Generative TPs produce real .NET types that can be serialized normally. FSharp.Data uses erased TPs, but if your schema is fixed you could also consider hand-writing the record types (or using an XSD-to-record code generator).

